<time>1621803262146</time><rating>5< /rating><text>Assalaam u Alekum
March 5th, 2021  ANNOUNCEMENT

We are now back to ONE Jumma Salah and we offer both indoor outdoor accomodations by the grace of Allah . But we are strictly following the COVID 19 guidelines of maintaining 6ft distancing and mask wearing. Our Jumma khutba starts at 1:10pm followed by prayer at 1:30pm.
We are encouraging sisters to perform their prayers at home  at the moment due to lack of space at the masjid.

Apart from Friday Jumma, we are also open for 5 times prayers.

Please make sure to follow all Covid 19 related guidelines , Masks are mandatory,  bring your own Prayer rug, social distancing,  perform Wadu at home, no chit chat after Salah
Jazak Allah for your understanding and cooperation.
_--++++++++++++++++++++++
Ramadan Announcement:

Due to the ongoing Covid 19 Pandemic situation ICNOHO Ramadan programming will be as follows:

1. THERE WILL BE NO IFTAR                      PROGRAM
2. Masjid will have Dates ,   fruit and drink available for Iftar for any one stopping by for Maghrib Salah.
3.Traweeh will be conducted (20 Rakah) during the month. It will be shorter version than normal.
4. All Covid related CDC guidelines will be followed...social distancing,  Mask should be worn, Bring your own Prayer rug etc.
5. At present we are recommending women should not attend. We will further review this matter during Ramadan.

6. Itteqaf during the last 10 days of Ramadan will be allowed to only 3 individuals. Please request early if you want to do so.
May Allah Subanaho Tala
guide us to fulfill our obligations during the month of Ramadan.  Aameen.

< userid>
102758659627134250746< /userid>
<Name>Arnold Gallegos</Name><Pics>None<//Pics><Resp>None< /Resp>< Review>
There's no negative star rating so 1 is all this buisness deserves.

My mom came to this location out of curiosity to see how much she could save in comparison to her then current provider.

The rep managed to sell her on the cheap service rate. She then went into the prices of the phones this threw my mom off since she spent so much on her previous GalaxyS5 phone so she said she would come back when she could afford a new phone.

Well the rep jumped into sales mode and told her she could use her phone after minutes of stalling it was obvious the phone was not compatible with crickets chip the rep told my mom her phone was old and could not work and she should trade it in for a credit for the new phone. My mom a nieve senior believed this greedy sales person then she asked my mom to sign a "WAIVER" saying she gives up her right to reclaim her phone.

The phone she was given was a cheap knock off at 40% off because she traded her GalaxyS5. I went in to reclaim her phone and the manager David said the phone was already taken to headquaters and we were SOL.

I asked for his business card he said he had none I asked for his district's managers info he said he had none. This estblishment preys on nieve consumers then protect themselves with waivers once consumers had figured they have been screwed.

The worst part is all the people who work here are young taking advatage older seniors.<//Review>

<text>I've lived in Carmichael for over 30 years and have nothing bad to say regarding the Carmichael post office, I've had a box with them ever since they were on Palm and have always found them to be professional and courteous.

I will say that I do feel bad for the garbage they have to deal with from some of the more obnoxious patrons . I run a home based business and as such am in the post office 3 or 4 times a week it's about a 2.5 mile walk from my house and I walk there almost every morning. At one time Carmichael was a nice place to live, it was the type of community where on your walk to the post office people would take the time to say good morning to each other.

Well that all changed after the rents skyrocketed, The more conservative Carmichael became the more obnoxious and rude people became, Seems like the conservative better than thou crowd has moved in and they simply have no time to be pleasant or courteous.

It seems like every time I'm in the post office there's some inconsiderate buffoon in there making a fuss out of nothing usually the same person who's on the phone babbling about the Kenyan in office ,

More often than not it's some woman glued to her phone and then when it's her turn at the counter she has the audacity to get mad at the poor guy behind the counter because he cant figure if she's talking to him or the person on the other end of her phone..

It would be hilarious if it didn't slow the line down so much.. There is an old Bible quote regarding treating others as you wish to be treated and I'm thinking that many of the people posting bad reviews calling people morons should take a long cold hard look in the mirror, Chances are more likely than not it's you're own inconsiderate, obnoxious attitude that is responsible for your bad experiences in life..< /text>< Rating>

<Rate>3</Rate><Review>When my family and I leave for vacations (averaging 4 days or so), we have my dog board here.

Upon seeing the place in which my dog would stay, I was so sad to see that the conditions were/are very poor. The hospital's website states: "On occasion when we go out of town we need a place for our furry family member to stay while we are gone. Your pet can stay in a temperature controlled environment where he/she will be loved and cared for by our staff. He/she will stay in a spacious dog run with views of his/her neighbors and talk to the others about their great family and how much they are loved."

This is all complete bullshit. They sleep in caged, wired boxes(essentially) on a cold, hard cement floor. I hope that they at least provide them with a blanket considering they are sleeping on bare cement and during the winter time. The dogs in there are miserable; though it is true the dogs will view their "neighbors", it is because they have so little space. I do not buy any of their tempered, cutesy rhetoric. The staff are both nice and lifeless, basically.

I cannot speak for their medical services because my pet has only received shots from this place, no surgery or urgent medical treatment.

Tl;dr - if you love your pet, please do not board them here. You get what you pay for<//Review><pics>None<//pics><Response>None</Response>< gmap_id>

The OWNER was YELLING at me, the customer, accusing me of having my dates wrong, however all of my confirmations through Priceline were for the correct date. The owner refused to acknowledge that his system was at fault.

I call up Priceline, double check with them, and they had the correct dates, and they contacted the owner of the hotel to fix my dates. After not hearing back for a couple days, I cancel my order (which I still had 2.5 weeks before I should even be charged for any stay).

1. We canceled.
2. We never even set foot on their premise.
3. They had the wrong dates for our stay.
4. They didn't even have authority to charge us (canceled within the $0 booking time frame).
5. The amount they charged was a few dollars MORE than the amount on my CANCELED Priceline receipt of what we would have paid.

0x80c2bf1f68d9c3e1:0xeb6245d12e254ab4</gmapID>
<text>Trendy Japanese-esque restaurant with views of LA. Came here for a birthday dinner, and they currently have outdoor and indoor seating during covid. They accept reservations for large groups (we had 8 people). Valet parking only ($12, credit cards accepted). Be prepared to wait - even though we had a reservation and the entire group was present, it still took about 20 minutes to get seated. They seem to put the bigger groups in the back of the restaurant, but if you come in a group of two, try to get seated by the garden (it‚Äôs very pretty). There‚Äôs a bar to grab a drink while you‚Äôre waiting or you can walk around and check out the views. There was a private event going on that night so unfortunately we weren‚Äôt able to see the golden Buddha.

Food-wise, it‚Äôs shareable plates. My thoughts are as follows:

- Grilled Branzino - the Angel hair pasta that accompanied the fish was the unexpected standout of the night. Get this.
- Duck salad: this was alright, I wish there was more dressing throughout the greens
- Lobster roll: our waiter recommended this; it‚Äôs a warm, saucy mess but it‚Äôs good
-Potstickers: standard fried dumplings; they come in four
-Soy ginger pork ribs: good dish to split; the sauce is on the sweeter side
-  Spicy prawn noodles: I liked the texture of the noodles and there was a subtle hint of spice, but note the two prawns‚Äô heads are still attached. Our group ended up not eating the prawns (that reflects our own laziness than the restaurant), but good to note for larger groups who might be awkward about sharing
-Braised short rib: a bit disappointing; not as tender as I would‚Äôve expected

Service-wise, our waiter was nice but did not check in on us. We had to flag multiple people down to get water refills. We were also not given an order of truffle chips but were still charged (our group just paid it anyways). Credit cards are accepted and you can split the check multiple ways. Note that you have to take stairs down to get to the bathrooms, and there was always a long line.

Overall, it‚Äôs a trendy restaurant and the building is pretty, but the food is of little substance. You‚Äôre paying for the views and the ambiance. Good for date nights/special occasions/when someone else is paying.< /text></record></dataset><record>

<userid>109053396035696393048<//userid>< Name>
Ghen L.<//Name>
< Time>
1614617521886< /Time>
<rating>4<//rating>< Text>
The view and ambiance, even with Covid-19 protocols in place, definitely 5 stars. The food averaged at 4, 4.5 stars for us from a taste perspective. For the price it tasted good, just not exceptional. It all looked beautiful so 5 stars for presentation, but again, just seemed to not get me to the 5 stars. The roasted bone marrow bruschetta was delicious but they didn't have enough crostini for the toppings, the edamame was great with the truffle oil but wasn't a great value at $16. The pork belly yakitori seemed to be unevenly grilled so the fatty parts were a little undercooked while the meat itself was a little dry. The wagyu beef with garlic yakitori was much better. The hibachi pineapple fried rice was one of the highlights for us. The 6 year old loved it and they were able to accommodate for egg allergies. We dug out the rest of the pineapple after eating all the rice so it was a little dessert too. The Ishi Yaki cooking stone with American wagyu was delicious and enough to share for 2 people although 1 person could eat it all if they didn't order anything else. If this was all we ordered it would have been 5 stars. The spicy tuna crispy rice for a thumbs down from our party as the sweet sauce was over powering and not disclosed on the menu so that brought our rating down by a lot. For dessert we ordered the chocolate drama and shared it... It could have used some whipped cream or more berries - something to cut all the chocolate sweetness to it but perhaps that was intentional for the drama! Overall will definitely go again just will steer clear of the crispy rice and pork belly offerings.< /Text>

< text>
The good: Views, ambiance, location

The bad: Food

The ugly: Customer service

Seriously. Went tonight for the first time. The location was cool, as was the atmosphere. Definitely great for a date or a special night out, but the views are about where the good ends. The customer service was terrible. It was a little busy, but it wasn‚Äôt anything outside of what you would expect for a place like that. I‚Äôve had better service at a Buffalo Wild Wings during a Pittsburgh Steelers playoff game and a NASCAR race. My group of 6 had to ask multiple times for drinks. We ordered Edamame as an appetizer and it didn‚Äôt come until it was asked for again and an hour after the main courses came out. Half of my group didn‚Äôt get their fried rice until an hour after the other half got their sushi rolls. When we asked why fried rice was taking over an hour and a half to be served, our waitress was completely ignored by her manager and in turn we were completely ignored by her until our food finally came out. Our food was mediocre at best. My local sushi place could give this place a run for their money in terms of flavor and quality.  Very underwhelming service and food quality. Truly sad for a place with so much potential.</text>

<pics>None<//pics><Gmap_id>0x80c2bf1f68d9c3e1:0xeb6245d12e254ab4<//Gmap_id><Text>Amazing food and even better location + ambiance. Great service too.</Text>< UserId.>

<resp>None<//resp><Rating>5</Rating><Name>Azmat Shah<//Name></record></dataset><record>
<date>1544378647020< /date>< review>
The company I work for reserved the restaurant for our holiday party.  Although we had some rain on our drive in, the views were still amazing.

The ambiance also felt very relaxed and I did not feel out of place.  I was very pleased to be able to see Hollywood, Downtown LA, nearby mountains and hills.

This place is easy to get to, so I will add this to my list of places to go back to and visit again.

I also enjoyed the Buddha statue and was able to walk downstairs. I didn't get to see the other gardens and their poolside bar, but I can imagine that during the day time, it is just as gorgeous.

The staff on hand were very courteous and attentive with everyone!  I enjoyed my experience based on the Holiday party that was hosted.<//review>

<Rating>4</Rating><Text>The company I work for reserved the restaurant for our holiday party.  Although we had some rain on our drive in, the views were still amazing.

The ambiance also felt very relaxed and I did not feel out of place.  I was very pleased to be able to see Hollywood, Downtown LA, nearby mountains and hills.

This place is easy to get to, so I will add this to my list of places to go back to and visit again.

I also enjoyed the Buddha statue and was able to walk downstairs. I didn't get to see the other gardens and their poolside bar, but I can imagine that during the day time, it is just as gorgeous.

The staff on hand were very courteous and attentive with everyone!  I enjoyed my experience based on the Holiday party that was hosted.<//Text>< Name>

< review>
Fine dining at its best.
DATE SAVING TIP: The seating with the best view is primarily for groups of four or more. The intimate seating for two, may land you on the level below other dinners and it feels like if they cough, it'll come down on you and your meal, so when making a reservation, be very specific about where you are seated. Upper level or right by the windows. (You'll be so happy for this tip once there) The food is a foodie's paradise and the ambience is perhaps top five in Los Angeles.< /review>

< Text>
This place is pretty awesome. First off the view is amazing. They are located way up in the Hollywood Hills and have a perfect view of LA County. We were fortunate and got a clear night, we were able to see as far as Long Beach. This place is definitely pricey but worth the experience. I ordered the A5 Wagyu which was my first experience with Japanese wagyu and, oooo weee, it tasted like butter. I've eaten American Wagyu many times and it sure doesn't compare. Well worth the trip!< /Text>

<Rate>3< /Rate></record></dataset><record>
<Rating>1</Rating>< text>
Not what it use to be...

Yamashiro left me wanting less, the food lackluster and the service inexperienced.

Customer service: Although there were many food runners there were few waiters. Our waiter seemed to be all over the place and spread thin. While we were still waiting for another dish and our dessert we were already given our check! Like wait... a minute?!
We spent about 15 minutes waiting for soy sauce to a point where our crispy rice sushi became stale. Then about another 30 minutes after we finished our entree to get dessert....We ended up canceling our nigiri sushi that we ordered in the beginning because it never came out.

Food: We ordered uni sushi (never got), sushi tacos, A5 waygu surf and turf appetizer, tuna crispy rice, yellowtail crispy rice, ramen, branzino yuzu pasta, panna cotta. The flavor was mediocre, nothing ground breaking. You‚Äôre paying for the view not the flavor or quality of the food.

To clarify we ordered from the DineLA menu as well as the regular menu, our bill was about $275. We don't expect special treatment but if we're going to spend our money at least get the food out in a timely matter or be apologetic that it didn't?

Save your money, go to a local Japanese izakaya.<//text>

<Review>DO NOT WASTE YOUR TIME AND RUIN YOUR NIGHT! We had a reservation for 7 at 9 pm. We arrived at our scheduled time and were told that our table wouldn't be ready for 25 minutes. At around 10:30 pm, they brought the soy sauce to the table. We noticed that the soy sauce pot was infested with 100s of ants. No exaggeration. We informed the wait staff and they acted as if it wasn't a big deal. We had to ask them to wipe down the table given that the ants had spread at this time. <Text>The 3 stars are for the view not the food. For food, I won‚Äôt even bother to rate it.

With a Japanese name and nice exterior and interior, I expected that it‚Äôs a good Japanese restaurant but unfortunately it‚Äôs absolutely disappointing.

We ordered spicy garlic edamame to begin with and it‚Äôs served in a minute or so. Obviously it‚Äôs pre-made and ready to serve. One of the worst edamames we had.

To go with the sushi boat, we ordered a small bottle of nigori that‚Äôs sold in the supermarket $8-$10 but sold at $42 here.

When the sushi boat was served, my hubby and I were both a bit shocked. First the boat itself probably needed some repainting or something. For a $120 sushi boat for 2 people, I guess I expected more than just all-you-can-eat quality of fish. The quality of the fish they used to make the nigiris and rolls was way below average. You can see from the pieces of nigiris, they were pre-cut, dry and of course not fresh. The shrimp tempuras of the rolls were not fresh. No question that the tempuras were sitting under the hot light for some time. The two rolls were quite the same with tempura inside, the difference was that one was with salmon and Serrano chilly on top, the other one with spicy tuna. You can tell from the colour of the fish, they were all-you-can-eat sushi quality. The fish for the rolls were even worse. And the size of the nigiri was tiny!

We didn‚Äôt see at all the tables around us anyone ordered sushi, everyone else was eating hamburgers and ribs. It‚Äôs just not a place for sushi. But isn‚Äôt this a Japanese restaurant?

It is sad to see a nice Japanese style property not serving authentic traditional Japanese. The only Japanese things in this restaurant are just the name and the decors. It‚Äôs certainly a shame.</Text><userid>100598276512819858255< /userid>< username>
Susanna Wong</username>

<user_name>Cornelia J. Jude<//user_name><Time>1597755022335<//Time><rating>4<//rating>< Review>
Hands down, the freshest sashimi rolls I've ever had in my life! The ordering process is super simple: you walk in, grab a menu and a pencil, and go ahead and seat yourself at the bar in the center of the restaurant. The service was quick and efficient.  I ordered 3 hand rolls, which is only $11. This comes with salmon, scallop, and crab. The seafood is so fresh and delicious. The chef makes the rolls right in front of you and hands you a roll at a time. Make sure to eat the roll immediately while it's warm and fresh! This place has definitely been one of the highlights of my trip in LA so far!</Review>

I recently took my partner for an anniversary brunch here. First off the view was amazing! It was a little on the pricey side but that‚Äôs expected for location, and the quality.

< Review>
Ate here for the first time on vacation and was blown away by the ambiance!!!

Driving up you need to valet your car (which I expected by online reviews). We took a few minutes to look around, take pictures etc. we were created by friendly hosts, asking us where we would like to sit. We got a great view of the city and had friendly conversation with the lady sitting across from us.

A little later on, as we were working our way through the menu, live piano music started and I was blown away by the renditions of current songs on the piano (wish I could find the artist‚Äôs name.) We had the best time and made our trip to La that much better!!<//Review>

100+ Years on "The Hilltop" Yamashiros Japanese Restaurant is a SoCal Landmark!
For over 100 years Yamashiros Restaurant, located in The Hollywood Hills, offers its visitors stunning views of Los Angeles and Hollywood while dining on superb Japanese cuisine.
The famous restaurant features traditional Japanese style architecture surrounded by gardens and waterfall ponds that overlook beautiful vistas.
Yamashiros is the perfect location to meet friends,family or for a romantic date or couples night out!
The inner covered patio garden is another beautiful feature of Yamashiros where you can have a drink,dine or relax and unwind!
Speaking of drinks Yamashiros has a beautiful bar and cocktail area with superb drinks.
Needless to say the Japanese cuisine at Yamashiros is nothing less than excellent with steak,fish,chicken and vegetarian meals available.Delicious desserts are available as well.
The staff at Yamashiros is courteous,helpful and offers great suggestions to make your experience perfect!
After dinner sit outside and enjoy the view!
And don't forget the Hollywood Night Market at Yamashiros to stroll around for an added experience!
.
.
.
.

< Text>
You are definitely just  paying for the view.... We (party of 4) arrived on time , 6 pm as scheduled. We waited 30 minutes to be seated , they were fast on getting our order but we waited more than an hour for the food to be serve. We ordered tomahawk steak and wagyu beef over heated stone but the tomahawk was already cold and the heated stone was not hot enough to cook the side veggies included in the meal. We told  our server and he said he will send us a new heated stone but nothing came until we finished eating so we end up not eating the uncooked veggies. And worse thing, the person serving the food accidentally dropped 2 plates of dumpling plates on the floor , flashing all the orange colored mayonnaise sauce over my chanel purse and my suede boots. It was a traumatic bday experience for me. But Im not blaming the employees, maybe they were understaffed and they‚Äôre exhausted. Thank you to all the employees who work hard and serve us during this Covid time.< /Text>

<user>106385980351017590069< /user>< username>
Chris Gilbert< /username>
< time>
1528216898674</time>
< rating>
4<//rating>
< text>
Incredible views and an amazing setting add to the wow factor of this hilltop restaurant. We ordered 3 starters and two plates of sushi - salt and pepper calamari, pork dumplings, crab cakes, California tempura roll, and wagyu beef nigiri. Generally the food was great, but the calamari was battered in something that made it armour-plated and the tempura roll was actually the entire roll, deep fried, which cooked the salmon. It was tasty but lost all of the freshness I was expecting from the roll. $10 for a single bottle of Asahi was also pretty scandalous.
A great experience but very expensive and food not quite on a par with the setting.</text>

< Review>
Yamashiro means castle in the mountain.

There is a Japanese style buidling
on the Hollywood hills.

Therefore, you can easily see whole
city of Hollywood and Los Angeles
from this restaueant.

Especially, night scenery is really good.

You can choose  assorted Sushi,
Sashimi, Prawn& Scallop, Baby Back Rib,
Salmon etc. from the menu.

Foods are tasty and Scenery is good.

You can see Japanese style garden
in the middle of the restaurant.</Review>

<rating>4<//rating><Text>The view and decor were amazing. I've honestly had better food for less cost, but that doesn't mean it wasn't good or worth it because the scenery is a huge factor.
My main discontent was that we went for the New Year's party and dinner. It definitely felt like they overbooked. It was crowded and impossible to get anywhere (including the bathroom). The party goers and drunks spilled into the dining area regardless of whether or not they were actually dining and would block walkways. Took forever to get drinks from the "open bar" (that was really just the most basic stuff like soda or juice mixed with one hard liquor or beer). Not really worth the price tag for the party wristband since you'd have to have 12+ drinks or really like the entertainment (that was again impossible to get to). The dessert buffet if you were dining basically got trashed by the drunks by 10pm since it was across from one of the bar stations and no one was watching it/keeping track and there was adsolutely no division between it and the party. Coffee was long gone too. We were lucky just to get cookies. Felt sorry for anyone who came after us expecting something.
They were clearly understaffed. It took 45+ minutes for anyone to bring us the check and during that time we totally could have just up and left without paying because people were wandering to and from the party anyway (no one's card was on file), but we have principles and have worked the industry so we just waited.
Again the view and decor were beautiful and probably more picture worthy on a normal day, and the food was great, so I do still highly recommend coming here and would go again... Just not during one of their parties.<//Text><resp>{'time': 1546622001346, 'text': "Yi, thank you for sharing this honest feedback. < name>

< rating>
5</rating>
<Text>It was a lovely night out with my lady taking us here for our 1 year. It was extremely packed and traffic on the way up, but luckily she had reservations. We were seated within 10 minutes. In the meantime, we walked right across to enjoy the beautiful Japanese garden with ponds in front of a gorgeous view overlooking the Los Angeles cityscape.

Our waiter, Kamarco, was great at getting us started and helped create a flavor I was interested in by mixing two items on the menu. We had a multitude of items to choose from and we started off mixing the Honey Garlic Baked Wings with the Honey Sriracha Shrimp, making it a Honey Sriracha Baked Wings appetizer. We also got Oyster Shooters, expecting fresh Oyster Shells, but were happily surprised with the shot glasses made with a unique oyster concoction. We selected the Green Dragon, the Ninja, and the Samurai roll to follow through. It was all made to perfection.

Although we did experience a problem right as I was about to dig into my first roll, it was handled in the most professional and courteous way you'd expect any high end restaurant to handle it. For that, I will leave out the details and thank the manager Mika for being so welcoming and generous. It was a nice early birthday and an anniversary dinner. That sushi melt in my mouth and I'm definitely going to crave it again. The only thing I wouldn't get again would probably be the Wagyu Beef roll. The truffle oil was so overpowering that it felt like I dipped my steak in soy sauce and salt.

Lastly, the place had a fun history as it was originally built as a house in 1915 and eventually converted into a restaurant. Every Thursday night they also have a Street Food Fair with lunch trucks right next to it so maybe we'll stop by for that next time. Cheers!</Text>< UserId.>
100162148249128210632</UserId.>

<review>Came here for a private event: My friend's baby's 1st birthday! Great space for parties. Plenty of parking in the lot.

M Grill is a terrific Brazilian steakhouse. Nicely designed interiors with trendy decor, but the building itself (exterior) looks really dated. For dining, there is a cool self-serve salad bar with refreshing and delicious fruits, seafood, soup, cold cuts, and veggies. For the main courses, the waiters serve the variety of different meats to your table. It is all you can eat, so enjoy and devour to your heart's content. The meat selections of pork, beef, lamb, chicken, etc. are brought to the table and some are sliced from the hand held skewers. The quality and taste of the meats are excellent. Perfectly cooked to my liking, as well. Filet mignon, parmesan chicken, rack of lamb, top sirloin, smoked sausage, boneless leg of lamb, wagyu beef, beef ribs, & ribeye are just a number of meats I've had from their extensive menu!!

The servers are both friendly and accommodating here!! No complaints!!<//review><response>None<//response></record></dataset><record>

Yamashiro means castle in the mountain.

There is a Japanese style buidling
on the Hollywood hills.

<pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMhMzEhuix3lETVpENiCfl-PKaF4KoEmgWkYd7x=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPE77_qIGY1KYdvT6T-il4QwZR-4ktGDQVY_FZq=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPYyddMlhnkq12qnIjNWmEL6ldBAG91d_03JOkY=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNFMBroYV3qSyZgkhc-jxW3cmia9jHV0ciT5qX0=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOeHtoG6uKcVxfuKrbLinXoxSDjE01Bt-d9_IwQ=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOCFTB8VfDOqQzKnOlHkGvkfZ3zoZBGH9AGVqZx=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//pics><Text>Fun!!! This is my first time come to Yamashiro summer farmers market. The traffic in Hollywood is always a nightmare. Parking in the Mosaic church parking lot and take the shuttle is easier than driving up the hill. Shuttle is $5 per person (not per car), round trip. When you enter, you need the wrist band if you want to drink alcohol, if not, there is no entry fee. Live music is amazing and the set up is really "farm theme" which makes the night so chill and enjoyable. There are not so many local farms veggies and fruits, more like a vendors events where you get to buy some food, drinks, candles, clothes, etc., and then you can sit on any outside table enjoy the music and city night view. Love this farmers market event and will defiantly come back again!<//Text>< rating>

<Date>1528015273534<//Date>< username>
Jay Dix<//username>
<user>110167273612798785247</user><rate>5</rate>< Review>
This is a historic place that's more than one hundred years old. It has the absolute best views of all of Los Angeles! It's great for an intimate date, or for large groups. Yamashiro in Japanese, translates to mountain palace. And it definitely holds true to its name. The restaurant is Japanese-fusion. It offers some of the best sushi in town, as well as other non-traditional items, like burgers and tacos. The crab cakes are excellent. Have a drink outside next to the pool at the Pagoda bar while you you take in The View!< /Review>

<username>John Branch</username>< review>
One of the main places I wanted to try while visiting LA was Yamashiro. It has been on my list for a while. The first night I arrived, I made it my missions to go. It was fairly simple to make reservations online, although they were about 15 minutes behind schedule.

There was a mishap with the seating and I had to wait an additional few minutes, but once seated, the view and ambiance took over. The place is very nice and watching the sun set in the distance is something I‚Äôd highly recommend.

To start with, my wife and I ordered the popcorn shrimp. By far one of the best shrimp dishes I‚Äôve had anywhere. I wasn‚Äôt really sure what to expect, but it exceeding my expectations. After that I ordered a Malibu sushi roll, which was also one of the best I‚Äôve ever had. Once I was done with my roll, we ordered a Filet Mignon & Pineapple yakitori and a Chicken Negima yakitori. I really like the Filet Mignon, the chicken didn‚Äôt really blow me away, but it was still good.

Overall, I would recommend this place for sure. I‚Äôm a little sad that I don‚Äôt live closer as I could see myself coming here frequently.<//review>

< Text>
Upscale place in an amazing building built a century ago in the style of a traditional Japanese temple. Haven't been in the restaurant for several years so can't speak to the current quality of the food, but you know it's $$$. They do an outdoor "market" (street fair) on Thursday evenings in their parking lot with about 20 food booths, alcohol, etc. Great views of Hollywood & LA., live jazz... Nice atmosphere.< /Text>

3</Rate>
< review>
My partner and I came to LA for our anniversary and we booked this restaurant in advance solely for the ambiance and the amazing views. We asked them about a week before we arrived for specific accommodations and they said they could not guarantee it but they would try their best, which we completely understood; they are a fairly popular spot and we knew it would be a busy night before we arrived.

When we arrived in LA, we were extremely pleased that they were able to honor our request. The ambiance is as beautiful as is pictured in other posts, especially the seating in the garden area. The location is on a hill, with views overlooking LA, which makes for great photo opportunities.

The food is mediocre and not anything special, and our server was handling a lot of different tables so he forgot our orders twice and we had to remind him after waiting quite a while.

To be honest, I would come here only for the customer service and ambiance and I would recommend it for those who are first-timers to LA, but I believe the food and service has room to improve.< /review>

<GmapID>0x80c2bf1f68d9c3e1:0xeb6245d12e254ab4</GmapID><UserId.>103364277366093686210< /UserId.>< Review>
Went here for dinner as a prelude to going to the Hollywood Bowl.  They have a dine and ride package that includes dinner, plus shuttle to and from the Bowl.  Great idea since you then avoid the hassle of parking, the traffic, and waiting in the parking lot after the concert to be able to get your car out of the lot, since it is staked parking.

But even more importantly, the food here at Yamashiro was amazing!   Service was great.  We will come back here even with out going to the Bowl.

There were 4 us eating.  Two of us had the ribs, which were melt-off-the-bone tender, and the sweet potatoes served with them were yummy too.  The other two in our party had the salmon.  The portions were huge besides the quality being amazing.

I also had a sushi sampler appetizer which was very good.  And molten chocolate cake for dessert.  My husband had a trio of sorbets for dessert that he loved, and he is not even really a sorbet person.

Highly recommend this place!

Oh yeah - the views of L.A. are fabulous too</Review>

<resp>None< /resp><pictures>None< /pictures><Review>Best view! Good food!

If you go there on a Thursday late afternoon, you'll get to see the Hollywood Night Market as well.  You'll have an option to buy food from the market or inside from the restaurant.  The restaurant itself is sitting at a higher level than where the market is and on the top of the Hollywood Hills that gives clear views of downtown LA and Century City.

You can go there either by car, a shuttle bus and also walk.  Parking is hard to find and it's not easy to drive in such a narrow winding road.  The shuttle comes from Hollywood and La Brea where the Mosaic Church is which takes forever although it's a short walk from there.  If you decide to walk from the Hollywood Walk of Fame, then go north on  Orange st from Hollywood Blvd, cross the street at Frankin, and go left.  When you see the sign, walk up the street.  It's a steep slope and you'll feel  out of breath in that 10 min walk.<//Review>< rate>
5<//rate>

< review>
Definitely come here for the view atop the Hollywood hills. The restaurant is elegant and beautiful inside and out, with a Japanese garden and Buddha statue in front of this secluded pagoda. However, the food itself doesn't match the Japanese setting. I suppose Japanese-American would be one way to describe it, but even that would be overqualifying the food. Especially for what you'll be paying? You're not going to be paying for the quality of the food. You'll be paying for the spectacular view as well as quality service. Would come back the next time I'm in town, but I'd probably only order a drink.<//review>

<user_id>110078175566978535709</user_id><name>Riannon Methner< /name><date>1506100073764< /date><rate>4</rate><text>Came here when we were in town recently. I was so impressed by the reviews online and the views of the place. We ate here on a Tuesday night and it was still very busy! Seems like a place that would be busy every night though. We requested a table facing the pool pagoda and the city. Absolutely beautiful views, but even better outside on their walking trail. The service overall was just okay. Food took about 45 minutes and my second cocktail that I ordered never even came, yet we were billed for it. Our server however was nice enough to remove it from the bill and still bring it over to me. The ambiance was nice too, but I was surprisingly surprised by the attire of the guests. To me, this place looks like a high end dressy dinner. It was pretty half and half for those that did dress up and those that just wore jeans and a tshirt. Not a big deal to me, I could care less but I was a little shocked by that. Even with the moderate service, this is still a place I would recommend simply because of the views. Side note, do not walk here ladies. Take an Uber or Drive. There is a ridiculous hill leading up to it.<//text><Pictures>None< /Pictures>< resp>

<Rate>3</Rate><Review>Yamashiro is a beautiful restaurant both inside and out along with a spectacular food - even though the food isn't as good as the looks.

I had the 'Darth Vader' roll which is a black rice roll which looked cool but the taste was fairly normal.  The crunchy rice was probably a better bet.  The drinks too were a little shaky.  The saketini was a little light while another spicier concoction was too spicy.  My friend had a meat and potatoes dish that looked cool as well but the end result was fairly bland.

For a romantic evening, it's a definite recommendation.  Be sure to get a window view to see all of LA as you can walk around the interior whenever you want.  Parking-wise, there is a valet service as you come up the hill next to the Magic Castle.< /Review><pics>None<//pics>< response>

<rating>4< /rating><review>YAMASHIRO HOLLYWOOD
Los Angeles Historic Cultural Monument (LAHCM) #921

Yamashiro ("Mountain Palace" in Japanese) is a replica of a palace in Japan's Yamashiro province mountains near Kyoto and was completed in 1914.

Originally built by the Bernheimer Brothers as a mansion to house their Asian treasures, the history of Yamashiro Hollywood includes serving as the headquarters of the ultra-exclusive 400 Club during the Hollywood Golden Age in the late 1920's and a boys' military school during WW2.

Gorgeous restaurant but quite a trek to get to.  Great photo ops though both for the Japanese palace and the LA city view.<//review>< Pictures>

<Review>I have to say that this restuarant is no longer one of the best in Los Angeles. It has changed since the late 90's and has definitley gone down in value. The grounds/garden was unkept, sections closed off, and looked dry and like it needed more watering. The food is mediocre compared to what it use to be and for the price the portions are small and I know you can get better food from a lot of other places in Los Angeles! I visited this restuarant on March 29, 2019. It was my Birthday Dinner, and our party of 9 people, 2 which were a toddler and a baby whom did not order their own plate because they were sharing with their parents, So Only 7 adults ordered their own plates and the bill was just shy of $800!!!! My son explained to the waiter that it was my Birthday yet no one ever came back to sing Happy Birthday to me, yet another patron dining here on their Birthday was sung Happy Birthday to! Not to mention, the food was not good at all! The Salmon was excessively salty, the cris-cut fries or whatever those little potato things that came with the rib plate are were stale and tasted terrible!, the server never asked us if we wanted a refill so when my son asked to refill his regular lemonade the waiter told him he would need to purchase another drink and there was No refills on any of the drinks, not even Soft Drinks! Also the server rushed us because we were one of the last 2 customers In the restaurant. On top of all that, the gratuity was included which came out to be 165 bucks and in all honesty I don't think our server deserved more than 20 bucks! We all ended up leaving very dissatisfied and some, like myself, still hungry because I could barely eat the Salty Salmon I ordered. I will never recommend this restaurant again like I use to in the past. I honestly believe we could have gotten bigger portions, better service, FREE refills on our drinks, not been rushed, and the staff not forgotten to sing Happy Birthday to me if we had eaten at Norm's! Oh, and if we had eaten at Norm's we could have saved 650 bucks too!!! I do not recommend Yamashiro's unless u are going there just for the view!<//Review>< pictures>
None</pictures>

Slow service, smelly venue, good food.

When I order three champagnes and two Pinot Noirs I expect champagne, not Prosecco.

We got to our table late, the service while charming was slow and though the views where amazing the smell of burning fat was not encouraging. The food, when it arrived, was mostly excellent, but I was glad to get out of there. Big, kitsch, touristy, worth a miss.</text>

<Review>If it wasn't for the amazing view and Sushi this place would have been a complete bust. Everything is far more expensive than it should be for not only the portion size but even quality of food. Service was mediocre even after making note this was for a birthday dinner. First table was rocking back and forth and recieved slight attitude for asking to be relocated to the garden. Second server in the garden lost interest is us when we didn't show absolute praise with the food. Unfortunately the manager(assumed) didn't stop by again after we had been served or I would have expressed my discontent then.

I was excited to possibly try the Wagyu but after the pork spring rolls were served we held back from ordering entrees. They were dry and not seasoned well at all. Mountain Palace sampler was a repeat disappointment unfortunately and the portion sizes for both considering everything was stale and tasteless was an insult to injury. The sushi was very good in comparison but nothing better than I've had at other establishments nationwide for less.

If you're going to charge the customer for experience and landscape view alone I would shut down the restaurant and turn the facility into a Japanese museum. The atmosphere, view, and decor are amazing but the food was anything but that.<//Review><Date>1528605141777</Date>< Name>

BrainFreeze LA<//user_name>
<Time>1545148939274< /Time><Rate>3</Rate>< Review>
My family and I used to go every year for my mother's birthday to Yamashiro's. My mom loved the traditional Japanese style and dress of the restaurant and the waitresses. The old menu was authentic Japanese cuisine mixed with a touch of modern and was absolutely delicious. The new style and menu is more Americanized and we weren't impressed.  Plus when you ask your waitress specific food questions and she stares at you like a deer in headlights that simply memorized the menu, it makes you wonder.. it was nice to venture out to Yamashiro's since it had been a few years since we all could get together and take my mom out for her birthday, but she said she wouldn't want to go back anymore. She prefered the old Yamashiro's restaurant.</Review>

<review>Incredible view without the noises of LA. Arrive early and spend some time outside along the paths before entering. The food was exquisite, with the two fish dishes we ordered, salmon entree and salmon sushi with pistachios being our favorite. Our Crisscut fries starter were cooked to perfection (how do they do this?) with ranch dressing and Japanese basil. The mixed drinks were standard LA price and some of the best I've ever had for $12. We came in early November, so the seasonal desert of pumpkin creme brulee piqued our interest. A delicious compliment to our other more sweet desert, S'Mores Fudge Brownie. Don't come here simply to eat. Come for the ambiance. Take your time to enjoy the food while looking over LA.</review>< gmapID>

< Text>
Reservations (-1 star) ‚Äì This place has a policy that requires you to make dining reservations by placing a credit card on file for large parties of 6 or more. I am not a big fan of this practice and regardless if you book through Open Table or make a phone reservation they require it. They do have in their fine print that last minute cancellations/no shows may lead in a charge‚Ä¶

Valet (-1 star) - It‚Äôs mandatory and its $9. They were extremely nice BUT if you are leaving with a large party it may take a while to get everyone‚Äôs car. The other alternative is to park in the residential areas and hike, but its Hollywood and signs are weird so I wouldn‚Äôt risk it.

Location (+1 star)- Getting here is kind of tricky and it‚Äôs certainly away from the busy Hollywood streets. When you arrive you really do feel like you are transported into a different era. It‚Äôs truly a grandiose compound!

Views (+2 stars) - The venue is LOVELY. I mean decadent with a garden and ornate d√©cor. The views overlooking LA is breathtaking especially at night when it seems like the whole city is twinkling. There are TONS of great photo ops here for ppl who love to take picks (both in the restaurant and around).

Food (+1 star) - Pricey yet delicious! I went with an indistinct sushi roll which was very tasty. Everyone in our party enjoyed their meals. It certainly carters to a diverse taste which offer loads to choose from depending on your taste.< /Text>

<UserId.>101500079640613512230<//UserId.><Name>Michael Z< /Name><date>1394850273659< /date>< Rate>
4< /Rate>
< Text>
Two of my friends and I decided to go to somewhere fancy shmancy the last we can actually meet up with each other before going back to school. When we go here, we were serious stunned by the view of the restaurant because you can see the entire city. You can also see a big sign that says trailer park too loool. There's also a small Japanese "garden" in the middle of the restaurant which is nice too.
Anyways the service was very good and the food was decent. It didn't taste amazing, but it was definitely better than any other Japanese restaurant I have been to.
We ordered two orders of sashimi, an order of poke, and an order of hamachi. The sashimi was very meaty and tasted fresh. The yellowtail was all right ... Didn't know why it tasted warm and that kinda bothered me. But oh man the poke was like the best I have ever had. Seriously if I were to come back ... I would definitely order a lot of the poke!  Overall the experience was awesome ! And this place is definitely worth a try if you're taking someone out on a date or something<//Text>

<user>101500079640613512230</user><Name>Michael Z<//Name><date>1394850273659< /date><Rate>4< /Rate><Text>Two of my friends and I decided to go to somewhere fancy shmancy the last we can actually meet up with each other before going back to school. When we go here, we were serious stunned by the view of the restaurant because you can see the entire city. You can also see a big sign that says trailer park too loool. There's also a small Japanese "garden" in the middle of the restaurant which is nice too.
Anyways the service was very good and the food was decent. It didn't taste amazing, but it was definitely better than any other Japanese restaurant I have been to.
We ordered two orders of sashimi, an order of poke, and an order of hamachi. The sashimi was very meaty and tasted fresh. The yellowtail was all right ... Didn't know why it tasted warm and that kinda bothered me. But oh man the poke was like the best I have ever had. Seriously if I were to come back ... I would definitely order a lot of the poke!  Overall the experience was awesome ! And this place is definitely worth a try if you're taking someone out on a date or something</Text>< Pics>
